ce:section.ce:para:
ESR and radical trapping experiments were performed to obtain more insights into active species in the system of NCS−4 (Fig. 6
                        ). ESR signals with a ratio of 1:1:1:1:1:1 (DMPO/MeOH), 1:1:1 (TEMP) and 1:2:2:1 (DMPO/H2O) were observed under light irradiation, indicating active species •O2
                        −, 1O2 and •OH were produced during photo−Fenton reactions. Moreover, the decreased triplet peaks with a 1:1:1 ratio in TEMPO were observed for h+. To further explore the active species during CTC degradation, radical trapping experiments were studied using TBA, TEMPO, AO and FFA as scavengers for trapping •OH, •O2−, h+ and 1O2, respectively (Wang et al., 2022). The addition of TBA, TEMPO and FFA led to decreased CTC degradation of ca. 55.7% ca. 36.0% and 54.2% (Fig. 6b), indicating considerable contributions of •OH •O2− and 1O2 towards CTC degradation. However, AO showed insignificant inhibition in CTC degradation, indicating a minor contribution of h+ to photo−Fenton processes.
